Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new board members for the US central bank, the Federal Reserve, gives Americans – and the US Congress – the opportunity to reflect on the world's most important central bank and its future path.
The obvious first question that arises is how it was possible for the Fed to miss its most important mandate – ensuring price stability – so badly.
The fact that the Fed was completely taken by surprise by current inflation points to a fundamental failure.
Clearly, institutional soul-searching is now warranted.
Yet while monetary policy makes headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
Another major question is therefore whether it will use its enormous power to advance climate or social policy.
For example, the Fed could refuse credit to companies in the fossil fuel sector, demand from banks that they only grant credits to firms with certified net-zero emission plans, or steer credit provision in the direction of desired alternatives.
Moreover, it could decide to explicitly take regulation for equality or ethnic justice under its wing, by dictating to banks where and to whom loans should be granted, who should be hired and who fired, and so on.
But before we address the question of which direction Fed regulation will move or should move in, we must first clarify the Fed's grave failure.
Im Jahr 2008 traf die US-Regierung eine folgenschwere Entscheidung: Finanzinstitutionen konnten sich das Geld für riskante Investitionen zwar weiterhin überwiegend durch den Verkauf von kurzfristigen, run-anfälligen Schuldtiteln beschaffen, aber Heerscharen neuer Aufsichtsbehörden würden die Risikoanfälligkeit der Vermögenswerte der Institutionen fortan beurteilen.
Die Hoffnung bestand darin, dass die Regulierungsbehörden keine dicken Brocken im Ausmaß der Subprime-Hypotheken in den Bankbilanzen mehr übersehen würden.
Doch in den darauffolgenden zehn Jahren detaillierter Regulierung und regelmäßiger szenariobasierter „Stresstests“ hat sich die Regulierungsarmee der Fed nicht ein einziges Mal gefragt, was eigentlich im Falle einer Pandemie passiert.
Als die Pandemie Anfang 2020 dann tatsächlich eintrat, verwarf die Fed ihre „Nie-wieder“-Versprechungen aus dem Jahr 2008 und intervenierte in noch größerem Ausmaß.
Im März erwiesen sich die Geschäftsbanken als nicht in der Lage, auf dem Markt für stinknormale US-Staatsanleihen als Intermediär aufzutreten.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed to the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. Correcting the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms had been put on the back burner.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed rescued the money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but they never happened.
Additionally, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially providing a guarantee on the "whatever it takes" principle.
In 2008, the Fed and the US Treasury Department had resisted the idea of setting a market price for all mortgages as part of the Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP) package for the financial industry.
However, in 2020, an explicit lower bound for corporate bond prices was introduced, among other things, with the "Powell put."
The predictable response to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to COVID-19 could have triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks because the Fed and the U.S. Treasury will simply extinguish every new fire with another flood of money.
The problem, of course, lies in the incentives these strategies have created.
Why bother with efforts to use emergency funds or balance sheet buffers for purchases when prices are falling, to provide liquidity, or to treat a "forced sale" as an "opportunity" to buy?
The Fed will always outshine everyone and scoop up all the profits.
Why issue stocks as a company when one can simply take on a loan, knowing that the state supports the debt or helps the company out of trouble, as was the case with airlines?
Why hesitate as an investor when buying dubious papers, when their value is guaranteed through another "whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed in bad times?
No wonder America is sinking into debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will pick up the losses during the next downturn.
Student loans, public pensions, and mortgages pile up, waiting for Uncle Sam's rescue operation.
But every new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Ultimately, bondholders will refuse to pour any more money into rescue operations, and people will not rejoice with trillions of newly printed money.
If the rescue packages expected by everyone do not materialize, we will wake up in a great fire – and the firefighters will be burned out.
In 2008, regulators and lawmakers at least recognized the moral risk and worried that investors would reap profits in good times while taxpayers would bear the losses in bad times.
In 2020, there was only self-congratulation over the rescue actions.
Genau die Fed, die 2008 die Risiken der Subprime-Hypotheken ebenso wenig kommen sah wie die Pandemie 2020 und die nun Stresstests im Hinblick auf „Klimarisiken” durchführen will, wird mit Sicherheit auch den nächsten Krieg, die nächste Pandemie, den nächsten Staatsbankrott oder ein anderes disruptives Ereignis übersehen.
Die Regulatoren der Fed stellen nicht einmal die Frage nach den erwähnten Ereignissen.
Und obwohl Buchstabensalate über „Vernetzungen,” „strategische Interaktionen,” „Netzwerkeffekte,” und „Kreditzyklen,” produziert werden, hat man es nicht geschafft, das „systemische“ Risiko überhaupt zu definieren, abgesehen davon, dass es zu einem Sammelbegriff wurde, der den Regulierungsbehörden allumfassende Macht verleiht.
Regulierungsbehörden werden niemals in der Lage sein, Risiken vorherzusehen, Vermögenswerte von Finanzinstitutionen genau zu bemessen oder sicherzustellen, dass immense Schulden immer bezahlt werden können.
Wir müssen die Grundprämisse eines Finanzsystems umkehren, in dem der Staat in schlechten Zeiten immer für Schuldenberge geradesteht. Und wir müssen das tun, bevor die Feuerwehr auf die Probe gestellt wird.
A better regulation can bridge party-political divides.
The Left is right when it says that the big banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit few Americans.
However, it starts with the wrong cause.
The massive effort required for compliance is a significant obstacle to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is pointless.
Regulatory provisions are either smart or dumb, effective or ineffective, full of undesirable consequences or well-conceived.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital offers a buffer against all shocks and does not require regulatory authorities to have prophetic abilities.
The Fed has scandalously stopped companies in the area of Narrow Banking and payment service providers that could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before she devotes herself to the rescue of the planet and the rectification of injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how poorly it fulfills its basic task of protecting the financial system.
